-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Show that cos (π⁄7) − cos (2π⁄7) + cos (3π⁄7) = ½. 2. [Key Idea] Multiply the required sum by 2 sin (π⁄7); judicious use of the product–to–sum identities makes every term cancel except one, leaving an immediate evaluation. 3. [Proof] Let a = π⁄7 and set S = cos a − cos 2a + cos 3a. Multiply by 2 sin a: 2 sin a S = 2 sin a cos a − 2 sin a cos 2a + 2 sin a cos 3a. Convert each product with 2 sin x cos y = sin(x + y) + sin(x − y): • 2 sin a cos a = sin 2a • −2 sin a cos 2a = −[sin (3a) + sin (−a)] = −sin 3a + sin a • 2 sin a cos 3a = sin (4a) + sin (−2a) = sin 4a − sin 2a. Add them: 2 sin a S = sin 2a − sin 3a + sin a + sin 4a − sin 2a = −sin 3a + sin a + sin 4a. But sin 4a = sin(π − 3a) = sin 3a, so −sin 3a + sin 4a = 0, giving 2 sin a S = sin a. Because sin a ≠ 0, divide by 2 sin a: S = ½. (Optional second proof via roots of unity is analogous but omitted for brevity.) 4. [Conclusion] Therefore cos (π⁄7) − cos (2π⁄7) + cos (3π⁄7) indeed equals ½.
